<subSubSection id="EBEABDD9FF94FFE939D30C204454BB96" lastPageId="27" lastPageNumber="254" pageId="26" pageNumber="253" type="description">
<paragraph id="A34FEE52FF94FFE839D30C2045CEB303" blockId="26.[136,1452,1814,2092]" pageId="26" pageNumber="253">
<emphasis id="91843240FF94FFE839D30C2047E6BC1F" bold="true" box="[136,200,1814,1840]" pageId="26" pageNumber="253">Trees</emphasis>
<quantity id="640843B7FF94FFE8398A0C20461BBC1E" box="[209,309,1814,1841]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.05" metricValueMax="2.6" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="26" pageNumber="253" unit="m" value="20.5" valueMax="26.0" valueMin="15.0">15–26 m</quantity>
tall; branch nectaries. 
<emphasis id="91843240FF94FFE83B630C2045A4BC1F" bold="true" box="[568,650,1814,1840]" pageId="26" pageNumber="253">Leaves</emphasis>
with 2–3 pairs of pinnae, opposite; 3–4(–5) pairs of leaflets, opposite; petiolar nectary 1, verruciform; leaflets 4.2–10(–12.8) × 
<quantity id="640843B7FF94FFE83A580C0C44ADBC7A" box="[771,899,1850,1877]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.7" metricValueMax="6.5" metricValueMin="2.9" pageId="26" pageNumber="253" unit="cm" value="4.7" valueMax="6.5" valueMin="2.9">2.9–6.5 cm</quantity>
, apex usually apiculate, sometimes acute, margin flat to slightly revolute, slightly undulate, subcoriaceous, discolor, upper surface glabrous, lower surface usually puberule, sometimes sparsely pubescent to pubescent, more densely along the midrib, unilateral tuft of trichomes on lower surface absent. 
<emphasis id="91843240FF94FFE838DB0C904505BCEF" bold="true" box="[384,555,1958,1984]" pageId="26" pageNumber="253">Sinflorescence</emphasis>
a pleiothyrsus; cymulae of solitary, geminate to ternate spikes, spike 
<quantity id="640843B7FF94FFE83C190C904285BCEE" box="[1346,1451,1958,1985]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.75" metricValueMax="5.5" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="26" pageNumber="253" unit="cm" value="4.75" valueMax="5.5" valueMin="4.0">4–5.5 cm</quantity>
long; spike prophylls late deciduous, ca. 
<quantity id="640843B7FF94FFE83B3A0CFC458ABCCA" box="[609,676,1994,2021]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="26" pageNumber="253" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
long. 
<emphasis id="91843240FF94FFE83BAB0CFC4461BCCB" bold="true" box="[752,847,1994,2020]" pageId="26" pageNumber="253">Flowers</emphasis>
monoclinous, purplish, anther gland sessile. 
<emphasis id="91843240FF94FFE83C0C0CFC42BBBCCB" bold="true" box="[1367,1429,1994,2020]" pageId="26" pageNumber="253">Fruit</emphasis>
a nucoid legume, usually straight, sometimes slightly curved, subturgid, 7–8.5 × 
<quantity id="640843B7FF94FFE83AA00CD84354B326" box="[1019,1146,2030,2057]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.55" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="26" pageNumber="253" unit="cm" value="1.55" valueMax="1.8" valueMin="1.3">1.3–1.8 cm</quantity>
, valves coriaceous, reddish dark-brown and ferruginous-pulverulent, glabrescent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A34FEE52FF95FFE939E60BA84454BB96" blockId="27.[136,1452,158,977]" box="[189,890,158,185]" pageId="27" pageNumber="254">
<emphasis id="91843240FF95FFE939E60BA8468EBB97" bold="true" box="[189,416,158,184]" pageId="27" pageNumber="254">Vernacular names:</emphasis>
— 
<emphasis id="91843240FF95FFE938E70BA84519BB97" box="[444,567,158,184]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="254">Tachi-rana</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="91843240FF95FFE93B1E0BA94587BB97" box="[581,681,159,184]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="254">Taxirana</emphasis>
or rarely 
<emphasis id="91843240FF95FFE93A4C0BA94454BB96" box="[791,890,159,185]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="254">
<taxonomicName id="64F095D1FF95FFE93A4C0BA94458BB96" authorityName="Casari" authorityYear="2017" box="[791,886,159,185]" class="Insecta" family="Elateridae" genus="Cumaru" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cumarú</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
